sales = read.csv(file.choose())
plot(sales$Sales.Units)

#Summary of Import Data -The first step before forecasting is to import the data. We can observe below that the data needs to be converted to times series in order to compare the different forecast methods.

#Plot and Inference #Show a time series plot.

sales_data = sales$Sales.Units
sales_ts = ts(sales_data, frequency = 12, start = c(2019, 1))
plot(sales_ts)

sales_win = window(sales_ts, frequency = 12, start = c(2022, 1))
plot(sales_win)

#Please summarize your observations of the time series plot -In the graph above we can observe a cyclical event in the year of 2020. In order to forecast for the future months, we need to exclude all the data before 2020.

#Central Tendency #What are the min, max, mean, median, 1st, and 3rd Quartile values of the times series?

#For which month is the time series value high, and for which month is it low? -The month with the lowest value in the time series is December and the one with the highest value is April.

#Can you think of the reason behind the high and low values in those months? -In the month of December, usually families prefer to stay at home due to the cold weather. Also as the holidays approaches families gather together at home and tend to go out less lowering the car’s sales. Meanwhile, in the month of April is where the warm weather starts and families go out more often, therefore increasing the need of a car.

#Simple Moving Averages #Plot the graph for the time series. #Show the Simple Moving average of order three on the plot above in Red #Show the Simple Moving average of order six on the plot above in Blue #Show the Simple Moving average of order nine on the plot above in Green

mae6_sales = ma(sales_win,order = 6)
mae9_sales = ma(sales_win,order = 9)

#What is the value of beta? What does that value signify?

-The value of alpha is 0.0002. The beta value controls the weight of the trend component, higher values gives more weight to recent observations. In this case, the beta value indicates the trend component remains constant over time.

#What is the value of gamma? What does that value signify?

-The value of gamma is 0.9997. The gamma values control the weight of the seasonal component, higher values gives weights to the more recent observations of the seasonality.

#What is the value of initial states for the level, trend, and seasonality? What do these values signify?

#Separately define each forecast method and why it is useful. Show the best and worst forecast method for each of the accuracy measures.

Naive: -The naive method will take the previous data to forecast the next value and assumes no trend, seasonality or any fluctuations.Naive is very simple to forecast and could be the baseline to compare to other methods. Exponential Smoothing: -The exponential smoothing calculates the next forecast value as a weighted average of the actual value. With the weighted average it give more weight to more recent data and ca be beneficial when the analysis has trend data. Holt-Winters: -The Holt-Winter method could be apply when the data has level, trend and seasonality. Also, holt-winters can be use for additive and multiplicative forecasts.
